 Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1210–":"about 1210–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1214–Female":"1214–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1172–Male":"1172–Deceased","1183–Female":"1183–Deceased","Abt 1240":"about 1240","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1214":"1214","Abt 1245":"about 1245","1245":"1245","Abt 1210":"about 1210","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","Abt 1235":"about 1235","1250":"1250","1183":"1183","1172":"1172","of Bretherton &, Croston, Lancashire, England":"Bretherton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Banastre was born about 1210, in Bretherton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam Banastre, was 40 and his mother, Mrs- Adam Banastre, was 29. He married Mrs- Richard Banastre about 1235, in Bretherton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1172–Male":"1172–Surnud","1183–Female":"1183–Surnud","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1214":"1214","Abt 1245":"umbes 1245","1245":"1245","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","Abt 1235":"umbes 1235","1250":"1250","1183":"1183","1172":"1172","of Bretherton &, Croston, Lancashire, England":"Bretherton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1210–":"noin 1210–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1214–Female":"1214–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1172–Male":"1172–Kuollut","1183–Female":"1183–Kuollut","Abt 1240":"noin 1240","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1214":"1214","Abt 1245":"noin 1245","1245":"1245","Abt 1210":"noin 1210","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","Abt 1235":"noin 1235","1250":"1250","1183":"1183","1172":"1172","of Bretherton &, Croston, Lancashire, England":"Bretherton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1210–":"environ 1210–Décédé","1210–Male":"1210–Décédé","1214–Female":"1214–Décédée","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1245–Male":"1245–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1172–Male":"1172–Décédé","1183–Female":"1183–Décédée","Abt 1240":"environ 1240","Abt 1250":"environ 1250","1214":"1214","Abt 1245":"environ 1245","1245":"1245","Abt 1210":"environ 1210","1210":"1210","1240":"1240","Abt 1235":"environ 1235","